div.div: why C overflow checks don't use CPU flags?

C's primary goal is to be a highly portable language, allowing code to compile and run correctly across a wide variety of architectures, compilers, and platforms without modification. This emphasis on portability strongly discourages the use of inline assembly for tasks like overflow detection, as assembly syntax and available instructions vary significantly between compilers (GCC/Clang versus MSVC) and architectures (x86-64's overflow flag versus ARM64's condition codes, with some architectures lacking direct support altogether). Relying on inline assembly would require extensive platform-specific code, violating C's core principle of write once, compile anywhere. A major obstacle is that signed integer overflow is undefined behavior according to the C standard. This means the compiler is free to assume that signed overflow never occurs in C language operations, enabling aggressive optimizations that may eliminate checks, reorder operations, or produce unexpected results if overflow does happen. Performing the addition in inline assembly and then inspecting the overflow flag does not itself trigger undefined behavior, since the operation occurs outside the C abstract machine as implementation-defined behavior. However, safe and portable detection still generally favors approaches that avoid potential overflow in C expressions altogether, such as the pre-check functions you showed. While GCC and Clang provide efficient builtins like __builtin_add_overflow that internally use hardware flags where available, these are compiler-specific extensions and not portable across all C implementations (unavailable in MSVC). This lack of standardization further reinforces why pure C pre-checks remain the common choice for general-purpose code. In summary, portability concerns make inline assembly an impractical choice for overflow detection in standard C.
Why is my use of std::uniform_random_bit_generator failing?

This is a tricky and a bit confusing C++ part even for me. So after a check on the `` documentation and C++20 Concepts, here is why: The Problem The uniform_random_bit_generator concept is failing because of two related issues:
Reference & Type Problem: When you use PRNG&& in your template, C++ tries to check the concept requirements on the reference type (like minstd_rand&), not the actual type (minstd_rand). Static Range Requirements: The concept requires static min() and max() functions because they define the range of possible values any instance of that generator type can produce. They're static because these bounds are properties of the generator type itself, not of specific instances (like how minstd_rand always generates between 0 and 2147483647).
Solution We have to either pass PRNG directly instead of passing it with a forwarding reference or work around the Concept Checks. For the second solution, we would use this: std::remove_reference_t So it would be something like this: template requires std::uniform_random_bit_generator> (1 more line was trimmed) Hope this was a helpful answer. Concepts are still a challenging topic for me in C++.

In my last project the build time would take around 4-6 mins so I switched to CMake. The first build was slow but the all the next ones were relatively fast. My question is:Is compiling only the changed files the only optimization made by CMake to improve build time? Also: How does CMake keep track of changes within files? How does it decide whether to recompile a file or not? I thought that maybe it saves the time of the last build and so checks last modification time of a file and compares it with the saved time. However I want to know the exact answer of it.
